  <!-- Features Widget *************** -->

  <Features classes={{ container: 'pt-0 mt-0 -mt-40' }} title="Korean Social Life, Health and Aging Project(KSHAP)">
    <Fragment slot="subtitle">
      The Korean Social Life, Health, and Aging Project (KSHAP) is a long-running longitudinal panel study designed to
      comprehensively examine the social, emotional, cognitive, and physical health of older adults in Korea. Initiated
      in 2011 and ongoing for more than 14 years, KSHAP forms part of an international effort to understand aging and
      quality of life through comparative, population-based research. The study follows the entire population of older
      adults and their spouses residing in two rural Korean villages, constructing a complete community-based panel that
      enables detailed longitudinal and network-based analyses. KSHAP adopts a multidisciplinary research framework,
      integrating social network analysis, survey interviews, physical and functional assessments, biomarker collection,
      and structural and functional brain imaging. By combining rich social data with biological, neurological, and
      health-related measures, KSHAP provides a uniquely integrated perspective on how social relationships, emotional
      well-being, cognitive functioning, and physical health interact over the aging process. The project offers an
      exceptional research infrastructure for advancing theories of social aging, health disparities, and life-course
      processes, while also informing evidence-based policies and interventions aimed at improving the well-being of
      older populations.

      <h3 style="margin-top: 2.5rem;">[Key Data Components]</h3>

      <ul style="margin-top: 1rem; padding-left: 1.25rem;">
        <li style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
          <strong>1) Social Network Data</strong>
          <ul style="margin-top: 0.5rem; padding-left: 1.6rem;">
            <li style="margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">
              - Real-name name-generator to capture actual discussion, medical advice, and emotional-support ties.
            </li>
            <li style="margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">
              - A complete community roster enabling the reconstruction of a near-complete sociocentric network,
              allowing global network analysis of social structure.
            </li>
            <li style="margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">
              - Longitudinal network data supporting the examination of reciprocity, network dynamics, and structural
              change.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
          <strong>2) Health-Related Measures</strong>
          <ul style="margin-top: 0.5rem; padding-left: 1.6rem;">
            <li style="margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">
              - Repeated measures of core health-related domains—including depressive symptoms (CES-D), cognitive
              function (MMSE-DS), and overall health status (SF-12)—assessed longitudinally across the study period.
            </li>
            <li style="margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">
              - Additional assessments of cigarette smoking, alcohol consumption and self-reported medical history of
              major chronic conditions.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
          <strong>3) Health Examination Data</strong>
          <ul style="margin-top: 0.5rem; padding-left: 1.6rem;">
            <li style="margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">
              - Objective measures of body composition (BIA), blood pressure and vascular function, bone densitometry,
              and physical function (TUG test)
            </li>
            <li style="margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">
              - Fasting blood biomarkers including hematological, metabolic, lipid, hepatic, renal, and inflammatory
              markers (e.g., glucose, insulin, cholesterol profiles, liver enzymes, creatinine, and C-reactive protein).
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>

        <li style="margin-bottom: 1.25rem;">
          <strong>4) Brain Imaging</strong>
          <ul style="margin-top: 0.5rem; padding-left: 1.6rem;">
            <li style="margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">
              - Multimodal neuroimaging including structural MRI (T1-weighted imaging, DTI) and functional MRI
              (resting-state and task-based).
            </li>
            <li style="margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">
              - Task-based fMRI paradigms included face-viewing and Cyberball tasks, probing social perception and
              social exclusion processes.
            </li>
            <li style="margin-bottom: 0.4rem;">
              - Brain MRI data were collected across multiple waves, enabling longitudinal assessment of brain structure
              and function.
            </li>
          </ul>
        </li>
      </ul>

      <div style="display: flex; flex-direction: column; align-items: center; margin-top: 2rem;">
        <img
          src="/kshapprojdesc.png"
          alt="KSHAP Project Overview"
          style="max-width: 900px; width: 100%; height: auto; margin-bottom: 2rem;"
        />
      </div>

